'''Delia Opekokew''' is a [[Cree]] lawyer and writer from the [[Canoe Lake First Nation]] in [[Saskatchewan]], [[Canada]]. She was the first [[First Nations]] lawyer ever admitted to the bar association in [[Ontario]] and in [[Saskatchewan]],<ref name=saskenc>[http://esask.uregina.ca/entry/opekokew_delia.html Delia Opekokew] at the Encyclopedia of Saskatchewan.</ref> as well as the first woman ever to run for the leadership of the [[Assembly of First Nations]].
==Early life and education== A member of the Canoe Lake First Nation in northern Saskatchewan, Delia Opekokew is the child of Marguerite and Jules Opekokew.<ref name="LPPBio">{{cite book |title=Saskatchewan First Nations : lives past and present |date=2004 |publisher=Canadian Plains Research Center, University of Regina |isbn=9780889771611 |pages=101-103 |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=Ji14s_ESoooC&lpg=PA103&ots=EZM-JRtIuo&dq=%22Delia%20Opekokew%22&pg=PA101#v=onepage&q=%22Delia%20Opekokew%22&f=false |accessdate=30 September 2018 |format=Google Book preview |chapter=Delia Opekokew}}</ref>{{rp|101}} Opekokew did not learn too speak English until the age of 8.<ref>{{cite web |title=Delia Opekokew |url=https://indspire.ca/laureate/delia-opekokew-2/ |publisher=Indspire |accessdate=30 September 2018}}</ref> She managed to maintain her knowledge of the [[Cree language]] as a student over the course of eleven years spent between the [[Beauval Indian Residential School]] and the [[Qu'Appelle Indian Residential School|Lebret Indian Residential School]].<ref name="Adam" /> She pursued undergraduate studies at the University of Winnipeg where she received a bursary for first year students with distinction.<ref name="LPPBio" />{{rp|102}} In 1977 she graduated from [[Osgoode Hall]] with a Bachelor of Laws.<ref name="saskenc" />
==Career== In 1967 Opekokew became the first woman to sit on the executive of the [[Federation of Saskatchewan Indian Nations|Federation of Saskatchewan Indians]] and worked from 1968 to 1973 as an administrative assistant for [[Buffy Sainte-Marie]] assisting with the creation a Native American Center of the Living Arts in New York.<ref name="LPPBio" />{{rp|101}} Following her graduation from law school, Opekokew was the first Indigenous woman admitted to the Bar of Ontario in 1979 and to the Bar of Saskatchewan in 1983.<ref name="LawSocietyMedalBio">{{cite web |title=Awards 2013: The Law Society Medal |url=http://www.lawsocietygazette.ca/news/2013-law-society-medal/ |publisher=Law Society of Ontario Gazette |accessdate=30 September 2018 |date=27 April 2013}}</ref> From 1979 to 1980, as a partner at Zlotkin & Opekokew, she practiced civil and family law before acting as legal counsel to the [[Federation of Saskatchewan Indian Nations]] from 1980 to 1985.<ref name="LawSocietyMedalBio" /><ref name="saskenc" /> She later became an associate with Blaney, McMurty, and Stapells where she worked from 1985 to 1990.<ref name=saskenc /> She subsequently worked in [[First Nations law]] across Canada, including stints as a commissioner investigating the shooting death of [[Leo Lachance]] and as lead counsel in [[Kenneth Deane]]'s trial for the shooting death of [[Dudley George]].<ref name=saskenc /><ref name="LawSocietyMedalBio" />
Opekokew was the first woman to run for Grand Chief of the Assembly of First Nations' [[Assembly of First Nations leadership conventions|1994 leadership convention]].<ref>{{cite journal |title=FEATURES |journal=The Ambassadors |date=2006 |volume=9 |issue=1 |url=http://ambassadors.net/archives/issue19/profile2.htm |accessdate=30 September 2018}}</ref> She lost to [[Ovide Mercredi]].
She is currently a partner in the [[Saskatoon]] law firm of Opekokew, Johnstone-Clarke.<ref name=saskenc />
