A '''drug lord''', '''drug baron''', '''kingpin''', or '''narcotrafficker''' is a high ranking [[Boss (crime)|crime boss]] who controls a sizable network of people involved in the [[illegal drug trade]]. Such figures are often difficult to bring to justice, as they are normally not directly in possession of something illegal, but are insulated from the actual trade in drugs by several layers of underlings. The [[prosecution]] of drug lords is therefore usually the result of carefully planned infiltration into their networks, often using [[informant]]s from within the organization.

===Joaquín "El Chapo" Guzmán===
{{Main article|Joaquín "El Chapo" Guzmán}}
According to the U.S. [[Drug Enforcement Administration]] (DEA), Guzmán is the most significant drug lord in history.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/nathanvardi/2011/06/15/joaquin-guzman-has-become-the-biggest-drug-lord-ever/ |title=Joaquin Guzman Has Become The Biggest Drug Lord Ever |publisher=Forbes |date= |accessdate=2013-12-12}}</ref> He is well known for his use of sophisticated tunnels—similar to the one located in [[Douglas, Arizona]]—to smuggle cocaine from Mexico into the United States in the early 1990s. In 1993, a 7.3-ton shipment of his [[cocaine]], concealed in cans of chili peppers and destined for the United States, was seized in [[Tecate]], [[Baja California]]. That same year he barely escaped an ambush by the [[Tijuana Cartel]] led by Ramon Arellano Felix and his gunmen. After being captured in Guatemala, he was jailed in 1993  and in 1995 he was moved to the maximum-security prison called Puente Grande, but paid his way out of prison and hid in a laundry van as it drove through the gates. On 22 February 2014, Guzmán was arrested again. 
He is considered a [[folk hero]] in the narcotics world, celebrated by musicians who write and perform ''[[narcocorrido]]s'' (drug ballads) extolling his exploits.<ref name="WSJ2009-06-13">{{cite web | url = https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124482379191510287 | title = 'He Leads a Gang of Mafioso Gunmen': Songs in Honor of Mexico's 'El Chapo' | accessdate = 2010-12-01 | date = June 13, 2009 | work = The Wall Street Journal}}</ref> For example, Los Traviezos recorded a ballad extolling his life on the run.<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Grayson | first1 = George | title = Mexico: narco-violence and a failed state? | publisher = Transaction Publishers | date = August 31, 2009 | pages = 62–63 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=ogjkeCd7RGoC&pg=PA62&lpg=PA63 | accessdate = 2010-12-01 | isbn = 978-1-4128-1151-4}}</ref> In July 2015, Guzman escaped a second time from a maximum-security prison through a hole in a shower floor that led to a mile-long tunnel, ending at a nearby house.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/article/joaquin-guzman-loera-escapes-mexican-prison|title=Mexican Drug Lord Joaquin Guzman Loera Escapes Prison 2015 : People.com|author=|date=|work=PEOPLE.com}}</ref> A large-scale manhunt ensued. On 8 January 2016, Guzmán was captured by the [[Mexican Marines]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newyorker.com/news/news-desk/el-chapo-escapes-again|title=El Chapo Escapes Again|author=Patrick Radden Keefe|date=July 12, 2015|work=The New Yorker}}</ref>

===Jorge Alberto Rodriguez===
Jorge Alberto Rodríguez, also known as Don Cholito, is a notorious Colombian-Puerto Rican drug lord from [[the Bronx]], New York, who headed The 400 criminal organization, a dismantled secret cell of the [[Cali Cartel]]. Pulled into the drug trade at age 12, he left home at age 14 to begin working for his father, [[Gilberto Rodríguez Orejuela]], who headed the Cali Cartel.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}} Within six years he had made hundreds of millions{{clarify|date=September 2017|reason=US$, pesos, what?}} by shipping drugs from Colombia to nearly every U.S. state. He was one of the most-ruthless international drug lords unknown to law enforcement or governments.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}} During that time, the nation's{{clarify|date=September 2017|Which nation?  The U.S., Columbia, Puerto Rico?}} murder rate and cocaine-related hospital emergencies doubled.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}} He was arrested in 1990 in Tallahassee, Florida and sentenced to a 25-year prison term for a number of federal violations. Following his conviction, Rodriguez continued to operate his illicit business from behind bars, importing as much as {{convert|12,500|kg}}{{clarify|date=September 2017|reason=of what? drugs, cocaine?}} into the U.S. every month and ordering numerous murders of informants, witnesses, and law-enforcement officials in the U.S. and Colombia.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}} He reigned and flourished while incarcerated until he was placed in court-ordered high-security isolation in 1994.<ref>U.S. vs Jorge Alberto Rodriguez, 981 Federal Reporter 2d, Page 1199</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/FR-2009-04-23/html/E9-9294.htm|title=Federal Register, Volume 74 Issue 77 (Thursday, April 23, 2009)|author=|date=|work=gpo.gov}}</ref><ref>U.S. Bureau Of Prisons Prisoner Registry Number: 09086-017</ref>

===Pablo Escobar===
[[File:Pablo Escobar Mug.jpg|thumb|[[Pablo Escobar]]]]
{{Main article|Pablo Escobar|Drug barons of Colombia}}
Pablo Emilio Escobar Gaviria (December 1, 1949 – December 2, 1993) was a [[Colombian People|Colombian]] drug overlord. Often referred to as the "World's Greatest Outlaw", Escobar was perhaps the most elusive cocaine trafficker to have ever existed.<ref name="colombialink.com">{{cite web|url=http://www.colombialink.com/01_INDEX/index_personajes/narcotrafico/escobar_gaviria_pablo_ing.html |title=Pablo Escobar Gaviria - English Biography - Articles and Notes |publisher=ColombiaLink.com |date= |accessdate=2011-11-12 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928140737/http://www.colombialink.com/01_INDEX/index_personajes/narcotrafico/escobar_gaviria_pablo_ing.html |archivedate=September 28, 2011 |df=mdy }}</ref> In 1989 ''[[Forbes]]'' magazine declared Escobar as the seventh-richest man in the world, with an estimated personal fortune of US$25 billion.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.worldfinancialblog.com/entertainment/the-5-richest-criminals-of-all-the-time |title=The 5 richest criminals of all time |last=Zschoche |first=Sören |date=April 18, 2008 |work=World Financial Blog |accessdate=May 9, 2011}}</ref> In 1986, he attempted to enter Colombian politics. It is said that Pablo Escobar once burnt two million dollars in cash to keep warm while on the run.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/southamerica/colombia/6493894/Pablo-Escobar-burnt-1m-in-cash-to-keep-his-daugther-warm-on-the-run.html | work=The Daily Telegraph | location=London | title=Pablo Escobar burnt £5m in cash to keep warm on the run | date=November 3, 2009}}</ref>

===Griselda Blanco===
{{Main article|Griselda Blanco}}
[[File:Griselda Blanco Medellin.jpg|thumb|left|140px|Griselda Blanco]]
Griselda Blanco (1943–2012), known as the "Godmother of Cocaine", was a drug lord who operated between Miami and Colombia during the 1970s and 1980s. During the height of her operation, she smuggled nearly {{convert|3500|lbs|order=flip}} of cocaine into the U.S. every month through a network in south Florida.<ref name="cowboys2">{{cite video|people=Corben, Billy (director); Cosby, Charles (himself); Blanco, Griselda (herself)|date=July 29, 2008|title=Cocaine Cowboys 2: Hustlin' with the Godmother|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1176726|medium=DVD|publisher=Magnolia Home Entertainment|accessdate=October 3, 2010|ASIN=B00180R03Q|id={{UPC|876964001366}}}}</ref> She was noted for her ruthlessness and use of extreme violence, employing tactics such as publicly assassinating people in broad daylight, bayoneting a rival trafficker inside [[Miami International Airport]], and inventing the [[drive-by shooting|drive-by motorcycle shooting]] execution method.<ref name="vice">{{cite web|last1=Corben|first1=Billy|title=Griselda Blanco: So Long and Thanks for All the Cocaine|url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/3b5jz8/griselda-blanco-so-long-and-thanks-for-all-the-cocaine|website=Vice|accessdate=24 July 2017|language=en-us|date=2 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Greene|first1=David|title='Godmother' Of Cocaine Trade Murdered In Colombia|url=https://www.npr.org/2012/09/06/160649616/godmother-of-cocaine-trade-murdered-in-colombia|website=NPR Morning Edition|accessdate=24 July 2017|date=6 September 2012}}</ref> It was estimated that she was responsible for the homicides of 200 people in Colombia, Florida, New York, and California.<ref name="vice"/> Arrested in 1985 for drug-trafficking charges, she was subsequently convicted and spent almost 20 years in a U.S. prison.<ref name=Villarreal2012>{{cite news|last=Villarreal|first=Ryan|title=Colombian Drug Lord Griselda Blanco's Life of Violence Comes Full Circle|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/colombian-drug-lord-griselda-blancos-life-violence-comes-full-circle-761125|newspaper=[[International Business Times]]|date=4 September 2012}}</ref> She was killed by motorcycle hitmen in Colombia on 3 September 2012 as she was coming out of a butcher's shop.<ref name=Godmother>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/world/godmother-cocaine-colombian-drug-lord-ran-miami-cocaine-empire-70-80-shot-death-motorcycle-gunmen-article-1.1151456|title=Godmother of Cocaine,' Colombian drug lord who ran Miami cocaine empire in 70's and 80's, shot to death by motorcycle gunmen|accessdate=7 June 2013|work=Daily News|location=New York}}</ref>

===Roberto Suárez Gómez===
{{Main article|Roberto Suárez Goméz}}

Pablo Escobar started to buy cocaine from Roberto Suárez in the 1970s when he had just created the [[Medellín cartel]].{{citation needed|date=July 2017}} Suárez started building cocaine laboratories in the middle of the Bolivian Amazon jungle and in the zone of "Los Yungas" in the end of the 1960s and created the first cocaine cartel in Bolivia called "La Corporación".{{citation needed|date=July 2017}} At first, the Medellin cartel bought cocaine at $8,000 per kilogram ($3,600/lb). La Corporación then sold cocaine-based paste to Colombian cartels, and they finished and distributed it in the east of the United States.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}} The finished cocaine was sold directly to Mexican cartels for distribution in the west of the United States. Suárez received untold amounts of money, but as detectives and journalists discovered the corruption between Bolivia and the U.S., the empire Suárez built began to fall.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}} Suárez was arrested by the DEA in 1988, and Escobar took over of the production and distribution of 80% of the world's cocaine.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}}

===Rick Ross===
[[File:Ricky Donnell Ross.jpg|thumb|upright|[["Freeway" Rick Ross]]]]
{{Main article|"Freeway" Rick Ross}}
Rick Ross (born January 28, 1960),<ref name="FBPRoss">{{cite web|url=http://www.bop.gov/iloc2/InmateFinderServlet?Transaction=NameSearch&needingMoreList=false&LastName=ross&Middle=&FirstName=ricky&Race=U&Sex=U&Age=&x=13& |title=Inmate Locator - Ricky Ross |work=bop.gov |publisher= Federal Bureau of Prisons|date= |accessdate=2011-11-12}}</ref> {{a.k.a.}} "Freeway" Ricky Ross, is a convicted drug-trafficker best known for the drug empire he presided over in [[Los Angeles]] in the early 1980s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usdoj.gov/oig/special/9712/ch06p3.htm |title=CIA Contra Crack Cocaine Controversy - D. Law Enforcement Investigations of Ross |publisher=United States Department of Justice Archive |work=USDOJ.gov |date= |accessdate=2011-11-12}}</ref>  The nickname "Freeway" came from Ross growing up next to the 110 [[Harbor Freeway]].{{citation needed|date=April 2017}} During the height of his drug dealing, Ross was said to have made "$2 million in one day." According to the ''Oakland Tribune'', "In the course of his rise, prosecutors estimate that Ross transported several tons of cocaine to New York, Ohio, Pennsylvania, and elsewhere, and made more than $600 million in the process."<ref>{{cite web|author=Scott JohnsonOakland Tribune |url=http://www.insidebayarea.com/top-stories/ci_17113312 |title=Oakland Tribune |publisher=Insidebayarea.com |date=2012-04-17 |accessdate=2013-12-12}}</ref>

In 1998, Ross was sentenced to [[life imprisonment]] after being convicted of purchasing more than 100 kilograms of cocaine from a federal agent during a sting operation. Ross became the subject of controversy later that year when a series of articles by journalist [[Gary Webb]] in the ''[[San Jose Mercury News]]'' revealed a connection between Ross's main cocaine source, [[Danilo Blandon]], and the [[Central Intelligence Agency|CIA]] as part of the [[Iran–Contra affair]].<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6r1KfHaIF_Y "NBC: Drugs and the CIA"]. [[YouTube]]. May 29, 2007.</ref> Ross's case went before the [[federal government of the United States|federal]] [[court of appeals]] and his sentence was reduced to 20 years. He was later moved to a [[halfway house]] in March 2009 and released from custody on September 29, 2009.<ref name="FBPRoss" />

In June 2014, Ross released his book, ''[[Freeway Rick Ross (book)|Freeway Rick Ross: The Untold Autobiography]]'', co-written by crime-writer [[Cathy Scott]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lasentinel.net/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=13160:rick-ross-book-signing-event-recap&catid=77:exclusive&Itemid=167|title=Rick Ross Book signing Event Recap  - Los Angeles Sentinel|author=|date=|work=Los Angeles Sentinel}}</ref>

===Manuel Noriega===
[[File:Manuel Noriega mug shot.jpg|thumb|right|180px|[[Manuel Noriega]], following his arrest by U.S. authorities.]]
{{Main article|Manuel Noriega}}
For more than a decade, [[Panama]]nian Manuel Noriega was a highly paid CIA asset and collaborator, despite knowledge by U.S. drug authorities as early as 1971 that the general was heavily involved in drug trafficking and money laundering.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}} Noriega facilitated "guns-for-drugs" flights for the [[Nicaraguan]] [[Contras]], whom the U.S. were heavily supporting: providing protection and pilots, safe havens for drug cartel officials, and discreet banking facilities.<ref name="Manual">Lormand, Eric (May 8, 2007). [http://www-personal.umich.edu/~lormand/poli/soa/panama.htm "Panama: The Resume of Manuel Noriega"]. personal.umich.edu</ref> He was arrested in 1990.

===Amado Carrillo Fuentes===
{{Main article|Amado Carrillo Fuentes}}
As the top drug-trafficker in Mexico, Amado Carrillo (1956–1997) was transporting four times more cocaine to the U.S. than any other trafficker, building a fortune of over $25 billion.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}} He was called El Señor de Los Cielos ("The Lord of the Skies") for his use of over 22 private [[Boeing 727|727 jet airliners]] to transport Colombian cocaine to municipal airports and dirt airstrips around Mexico, including Juárez.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}} In the months before his death, the DEA described Carrillo as the most-powerful drug trafficker of his era, and many analysts claimed profits neared $25 billion, making him one of the world's wealthiest men.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}}

===Miguel Arellano Félix===
Arellano Félix was a [[Mexico|Mexican]] drug trafficker linked to the [[Tijuana Cartel|Tijuana drug cartel]] (a.k.a. the Arellano-Félix Organization).<ref name=azstar1>{{cite web |url=http://www.csun.edu/CommunicationStudies/ben/news/cia/980415.steller.html |title=Mexican drug runners may have used C-130 from Arizona |accessdate=2007-09-26 |last=Steller |first=Tim |coauthors= |date=April 15, 1998 |work=The Arizona Daily Star |publisher=Archived at [[California State University Northridge]] |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080103194935/http://www.csun.edu/CommunicationStudies/ben/news/cia/980415.steller.html  |archivedate = 2008-01-03}}</ref> Arellano Félix was allegedly one of the most ruthless members of the cartel and was a suspect in various murders. He had been linked by Mexican police to the 1997 massacre of twelve members of a family outside of [[Ensenada, Baja California]]. The family was related to a drug dealer that had an unpaid debt to the Arellano Félix Cartel.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}} On September 18, 1997, Arellano Félix was placed on the [[FBI Ten Most Wanted Fugitives|FBI's ten most-wanted list]].<ref>{{cite web|title=The Business - Arellano-Felix Cartel|url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/shows/drugs/business/afo/afomembers.html|website=Drug Wars - Frontline|publisher=PBS|accessdate=24 July 2017}}</ref> In a sealed indictment in the [[United States District Court for the Southern District of California]], he was charged with conspiracy to import cocaine and marijuana.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}}

===Ismael Zambada García===
{{Main article|Ismael Zambada García}}
Ismael Zambada García is a drug smuggler in Mexico.<ref>{{cite news |title=Portrait Of A Mexican Drug Lord | url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2003/10/24/world/main579960.shtml |publisher=[[CBS News]]  |date=October 24, 2003}}</ref> Mexico's top anti-drug prosecutor, [[José Santiago Vasconcelos]], called Zambada "drug dealer No.&nbsp;1" and said the fugitive has become more powerful as his fellow kingpins have fallen, including one who was allegedly killed on Zambada's orders.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}}

===Klaas Bruinsma===
{{Main article|Klaas Bruinsma (drug lord)}}
[[Klaas Bruinsma (drug lord)|Klaas Bruinsma]] (1953–1991) was a major Dutch drug lord, shot to death by mafia member and former police officer Martin Hoogland.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}} Bruinsma was known as "De Lange" ("the tall one") and as "De Dominee" ("the preacher") because of his black clothing and his habit of lecturing others.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}}

===Arturo Beltran Leyva===
{{Main article|Arturo Beltran Leyva}}
Marcos Arturo Beltrán Leyva (September 27, 1961 – December 16, 2009) was the leader of the [[Mexico|Mexican]] drug-trafficking organization known as the [[Beltrán-Leyva Cartel]], which is headed by the Beltrán Leyva brothers: Marcos Arturo, [[Carlos Beltrán Leyva|Carlos]], [[Alfredo Beltrán Leyva|Alfredo]] and [[Héctor Beltrán Leyva|Héctor]].<ref>{{cite news | first=Antonio O. | last=Garza | coauthors= | authorlink= | title=President Bush Designates Beltran Leyva and his Organization Under Kingpin Act | date=May 30, 2008 | publisher=Embassy of the U.S. in Mexico | url=http://www.usembassy-mexico.gov/eng/releases/ep080530kingpin.html | work= | pages= | accessdate=2009-08-03 | language= | deadurl=yes | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090827010930/http://usembassy-mexico.gov/eng/releases/ep080530kingpin.html | archivedate=August 27, 2009 | df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | first=Penny | last=Starr | coauthors= |authorlink= | title=DEA Names Eleven 'Most Wanted' Mexican Fugitives Sought by U.S. | date=April 14, 2009 | publisher= | url =http://www.cnsnews.com/Public/Content/article.aspx?RsrcID=46528 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090615004009/http://www.cnsnews.com/public/Content/Article.aspx?rsrcid=46528 |archivedate=2009-06-15| work =CNS News | pages = | accessdate = 2009-08-15 }}</ref> The cartel was engaged in cocaine, [[marijuana]], [[heroin]], and [[methamphetamine]] production, transportation, and wholesaling. It controlled numerous drug-trafficking corridors into the U.S. and was also responsible for [[human smuggling]], [[money laundering]], [[extortion]], [[kidnapping]], [[murder]], [[contract killing]], [[torture]], [[gun-running]], and other acts of violence in Mexico.<ref name="DOS">{{cite web|url=https://www.state.gov/p/inl/narc/rewards/133310.htm |title=Narcotics Rewards Program: Marcos Arturo Beltran-Leyva |accessdate=2009-12-20 |year=2008 |work=U.S. Department of State }}</ref>  The organization was connected with the assassinations of numerous Mexican law-enforcement officials.<ref name="DOS"/>

===Frank Lucas===
[[File:FrankLucas.jpg|thumb|right|140px|[[Frank Lucas (drug lord)|Frank Lucas]]]]
{{Main article|Frank Lucas (drug lord)}}
Frank Lucas is a former heroin dealer and organized crime boss who operated in [[Harlem]], [[New York (state)|New York]] during the late 1960s and early 1970s. He was known for cutting out middlemen in the drug trade and buying heroin directly from his source in the [[Golden Triangle (Southeast Asia)|Golden Triangle]]. Lucas boasted that he smuggled heroin using the coffins of dead American servicemen,<ref name="Drugss">{{cite news|last=Vincent|first=Isabel|title=Where the drug lords are Kings|publisher=Maclean's|date=January 29, 2006|volume=120|issue=3|pages=23–24, 2p, 3c.|agency=Academic Search Premier|url=http://www.macleans.ca/world/global/article.jsp?content=20070129_140042_140042|accessdate=2011-11-12|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120531142110/http://www.macleans.ca/world/global/article.jsp?content=20070129_140042_140042|archivedate=May 31, 2012|df=}}</ref><ref name="Drugs">[https://www.usatoday.com/news/world/2007-01-20-mexico-extraditions_x.htm?csp=24 "Mexico extradites 'unprecedented' number of drug lords to U.S."]. ''USA Today.'' January 20, 2007. Retrieved November 12, 2011.</ref> but this claim is denied by his South Asian associate, [[Leslie "Ike" Atkinson]].<ref name="Drugsss">{{cite news|last=McKinley Jr., |first=James C. |title=Drug Lord, Ruthless and Elusive, Reaches High in Mexico|work=New York Times|date= February 9, 2005|volume= 154 |issue=53120|page=A3, 1/3p, 1 map, 2bw. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/02/09/international/americas/09chapo.html |agency=Academic Search Premier |accessdate=2007-04-18}}</ref> His career was dramatized in the 2007 feature film ''[[American Gangster (film)|American Gangster]]'' starring [[Denzel Washington]].

===Leroy Barnes===
{{Main article|Leroy Barnes}}
Leroy Antonio "Nicky" Barnes (born October 15, 1933) is a former drug lord and [[crime boss]] of the notorious African-American crime organization known as [[The Council (drug syndicate)|The Council]], which controlled the heroin trade in Harlem, New York during the 1970s.<ref name = "[[The New York Times]]">{{cite news |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2007/03/04/nyregion/04nicky.html |accessdate = 2010-05-02 | last= Sam Roberts |title = Crime's 'Mr. Untouchable' Emerges From Shadows |quote= | work=The New York Times | date=March 4, 2007}}</ref> In 2007 he released a book, ''Mr Untouchable'', written with Tom Folsom, and a documentary DVD of the same name, about his life.<ref name="Book">{{cite book | last = Leroy "Nicky" Barnes, [[Tom Folsom]]| authorlink = | title = Mr. Untouchable: My Crimes and Punishments|edition= March 6, 2007 | publisher = Rugged Land| isbn= 1-59071-041-X|page= 352}}</ref><ref name="Documentary">{{IMDb title|id=1086340|title=Mr. Untouchable (2007)}}</ref>  In the 2007 film ''[[American Gangster (film)|American Gangster]]'', Barnes is portrayed by Cuba Gooding, Jr.

===Zhenli Ye Gon===
{{Main article|Zhenli Ye Gon }}
[[File:YeGon millions.jpg|thumb|left|<!--250px|-->Part of the currency seized from [[Zhenli Ye Gon|Ye Gon]]{{'}}s home]] 
Zhenli Ye Gon (traditional Chinese: 葉真理;<ref name="Gilberto">[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/2417847.stm "Profile: Gilberto Rodriguez Orejuela"]. BBC. December 4, 2004. Retrieved November 12, 2011.</ref> born January 31, 1963, Shanghai, People's Republic of China) is a Mexican businessman of Chinese origin accused of trafficking [[pseudoephedrine]] into Mexico from [[Asia]]. At the time of his arrest, he had $207 million cash and 18 million Mexican pesos in his house. He claimed that he was forced by [[Javier Lozano Alarcón]], putatively identified as the Secretary of Labor, to keep it at his home and that this money would be used during [[Felipe Calderón]]'s presidential campaign in 2006. He is the legal representative of Unimed Pharm Chem México. The charges against him were dismissed with prejudice in August 2009<ref>{{cite web| url=http://legaltimes.typepad.com/blt/2009/08/federal-judge-dismisses-ye-gon-case-with-prejudice-.html |title=Federal Judge Dismisses Ye Gon Case With Prejudice |date=August 28, 2009 |last=Jeffery |first=Jeff |work=[[Legal Times]] |accessdate=May 12, 2011}}</ref> as a result of the efforts of his attorneys, Manuel J. Retureta <ref>[http://www.returetawassem.com "Returetawassem.com"] Manuel J. Retreat.</ref> and A. Eduardo Balarezo.<ref>[http://www.balarezo.net "Balarezo.net"]. A. Eduardo Balarezo.</ref>

===Christopher Coke===
[[File:Christopher Coke.jpg|thumb|200px|[[Christopher Coke]]]]
{{Main article|Christopher Coke}}
Michael Christopher Coke (born 13 March 1969),<ref name="aol">{{cite web|url=http://jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20100524/lead/lead4.html |title=Who is 'Dudus'? - Lead Stories - Jamaica Gleaner - Monday &#124; May 24, 2010 |publisher=Jamaica Gleaner |date=2010-05-24 |accessdate=2013-12-12}}</ref> a.k.a. Dudus,<ref name=nyr>{{Citation  | last = Schwartz| first = Mattathias  | title = A Massacre in Jamaica  | newspaper = The New Yorker | pages = 62–71  | date = 2011-12-12  | url = http://www.newyorker.com/reporting/2011/12/12/111212fa_fact_schwartz  | accessdate = 2011-12-26}}</ref> is a [[Jamaica]]n drug lord and the leader of the [[Shower Posse]] [[Jamaican Posse|gang]]. He is the youngest son of drug lord [[Lester Lloyd Coke]] whose extradition had also, prior to his 1992 death in a Jamaican prison cell, been requested by the U.S.<ref name=nyr/> Until the younger Coke's handover to U.S. forces on 24 June  2010,{{citation needed|date=December 2011}} "Dudus" served as the ''[[de facto]]'' leader of [[Tivoli Gardens, Kingston|Tivoli Gardens]] in the city of [[Kingston, Jamaica|Kingston]];<ref name=nyr/> prior to his 2010 capture Jamaican police were unable to enter this neighborhood without community consent.<ref name=nyr/>

The son of a prominent drug lord, Coke grew up wealthy, going to school with children of the country's political elite.{{citation needed|date=December 2011}} Ruling the gang where his father left off, he became a leader in the community of Tivoli Gardens, distributing money to the area's poor, creating employment, and setting up community centers.<ref name=extradite>[http://english.aljazeera.net/programmes/general/2010/06/20106301398204868.html Extraditing Coke.] Al Jazeera. June 30, 2010.</ref>

In 2009, the U.S. began requesting his [[extradition]], and in May 2010, a recalcitrant Government of Jamaica issued a warrant.<ref name=nyr/> That same month the government took steps to capture Coke. In a run-up to Coke's arrest, more than 70 people–all but one of them civilians–died in a 24 May 2010 raid of Tivoli Gardens.<ref name=nyr/> He was arrested at a Jamaican checkpoint on 22 June 2010.<ref name=nyr/>


[[File:Demetriusflenory.jpg|thumb|right|140px|[[Demetrius Flenory]]]]

===Demetrius Flenory===
{{Main article|Demetrius Flenory}}
Demetrius Flenory is known as one of the co-founders of the [[Black Mafia Family]], a [[Detroit]]-based drug-trafficking organization involving the large-scale distribution of cocaine throughout the U.S. from 1990 to 2005.<ref>[http://www.justice.gov/dea/pubs/states/newsrel/2008/detroit091208a.html "Black Mafia Family Members Sentenced to 30 Years"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110916143544/http://www.justice.gov/dea/pubs/states/newsrel/2008/detroit091208a.html |date=September 16, 2011 }}. September 12, 2008. ''[[Drug Enforcement Administration]]''. Press release.</ref> There are currently plans to produce a film based upon his career.<ref><!--<nowiki>http://www.examiner.com/crime-in-detroit/film-works-about-detroit-gangster-demetrius-flenory-black-mafia-family</nowiki>-->"Film in works about Detroit gangster Demetrius Flenory, Black Mafia Family" . June 25, 2011. Examiner.com{{dubious|date=November 2011|reason=unreliable source.}}
</ref><ref>Clark, Kevin L. (June 24, 2011). [http://www.complex.com/pop-culture/2011/06/the-black-mafia-family-movie-is-coming-soon "The 'Black Mafia Family' Movie Is Coming To A Theater Near You!"]. ''complex.com'', Complex Media.</ref>

==Current trends==
Following the death of [[Pablo Escobar]] in 1993, significant changes occurred in the structure or drug trade, departing from massive cartels such as [[Juan David Ochoa]]'s [[Medellín cartel]]. Drug lords have begun breaking the large cartels into much smaller organizations. In so doing, they decreased the number of people involved and shrank their role as targets—most likely in an attempt to avoid the fate of their predecessors. With newer technology, drug lords are able to manage their operations more effectively from behind the scenes, keeping themselves out of the spotlight and off the FBI and DEA wanted lists. These smaller cartels are slowly proving to be safer and more profitable for those involved.<ref name="NORQUIST">{{cite news |url=http://www.cnn.com/interactive/specials/0008/organization.profiles/drug.html |title=Special: Drug organization profiles - The Drug Lords |work=CNN |accessdate=October 29, 2007 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071029173707/http://www.cnn.com/interactive/specials/0008/organization.profiles/drug.html |archivedate=October 29, 2007 |df=mdy }}</ref>

Up until the demise of Pablo Escobar, in many instances, drug lords essentially ran the governments of the locations they controlled through bribery and assassination. However, this way of controlling their operations is becoming less prevalent. One of the most-notorious examples of the treatment given to drug lords is in the incarceration of Escobar. Although Escobar was, after turning himself in, jailed for his participation in drug trafficking in Colombia, the "jail" in which he was captive was a million-dollar palace built with his own funds. Another famous crime lord who enjoyed lightened jail life was [[Al Capone]], who continued to run his business from his jail cell, which contained tables, chairs, a bed, flowers, and paintings. For drug lords of the past, jail often served as a way to avoid further persecution.

In recent times, drug lords seldomly control local and regional governments, having less influence over their surroundings and their ability to continue to run their businesses from jail.<ref name="Drugss"/><ref name="Drugssss">{{cite news|last=Kershaw |first=Sarah|title=Dizzying Rise and Abrupt Fall For a Reservation Drug Lord |work=New York Times |date= February 20, 2006 |volume=155 |issue= 53496 |page=A1-A10, 2p, 2c. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/02/20/national/20gena.html?pagewanted=all |agency=Academic Search Premier |accessdate=2011-11-12}}</ref>

Another trend that has been emerging in the last decade is a willingness of local authorities to cooperate with foreign nations, most notably the U.S., in an effort to apprehend and incarcerate drug lords. Recently, especially in the last five years,{{when|date=September 2017}} countries have been more willing to extradite their drug lords to face charges in other countries, an act that not only benefits them directly but also gives them favor with foreign governments. Mexico extradited 63 drug dealers to the U.S. in 2006. However, extradition may be prohibited if the person faces the death penalty.<ref name="Drugs"/><ref name="Drugs"/>

