'''James Valoue''' (also spelled Valouë, Valoué or Valouè in various references) was an 18th-century [[watchmaker]]. He is most remembered for his 1737 design of a horse-powered [[pile driver]] which was used in the construction of [[Westminster Bridge]]. In 1738 the [[Royal Society of London]] gave Valoue the [[Copley Medal]] for his invention of "an engine for driving piles to make a foundation for the bridge to be erected in Westminster, the model whereof had been shown to the society".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://royalsociety.org/Content.aspx?id=3263|title=Copley archive winners 1799 - 1731|publisher=The Royal Society|accessdate=2009-11-18}}</ref> The [[Science Museum (London)|Science Museum of London]] holds a model of Valoue's pile driver constructed by [[Stephen Demainbray]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nmsi.ac.uk/collections/exhiblets/george3/horsepile.asp|title=The King George III Collection: Image gallery|publisher=Science Museum|accessdate=2009-11-18|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110610053808/http://www.nmsi.ac.uk/collections/exhiblets/george3/horsepile.asp|archivedate=2011-06-10|df=}}</ref>
