{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}} {{Infobox football biography | name = Stefano Lilipaly | image = | caption = | fullname = Stefano Yantje Lilipaly | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1990|1|10|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Arnhem]], Netherlands | height = {{height|m=1.75}}<ref name="Soccerway"/> | position = [[Midfielder|Attacking Midfielder]] | currentclub = [[Bali United F.C.|Bali United]] | clubnumber = 87 | youthyears1 = 1997–2000 | youthclubs1 = [[RKSV DCG|DCG]] | youthyears2 = 2000–2001 | youthclubs2 = [[AZ (football club)|AZ]] | youthyears3 = 2001–2010 | youthclubs3 = [[FC Utrecht]] | years1 = 2010–2012 | clubs1 = [[FC Utrecht]] | caps1 = 5 | goals1 = 1 | years2 = 2012–2014 | clubs2 = [[Almere City FC|Almere City]] | caps2 = 42 | goals2 = 8 | years3 = 2014 | clubs3 = [[Hokkaido Consadole Sapporo|Consadole Sapporo]] | caps3 = 0 | goals3 = 0 | years4 = 2014–2015 | clubs4 = [[Persija Jakarta]] | caps4 = 8 | goals4 = 1 | years5 = 2015–2017 | clubs5 = [[SC Telstar|Telstar]] | caps5 = 44 | goals5 = 9 | years6 = 2017 | clubs6 = [[SC Cambuur]] | caps6 = 17 | goals6 = 8 | years7 = 2017– | clubs7 = [[Bali United F.C.|Bali United]] | caps7 = 43 | goals7 = 17 | nationalyears1 = 2006–2007 | nationalteam1 = [[Netherlands national under-17 football team|Netherlands U17]] | nationalcaps1 = | nationalgoals1 = | nationalyears2 = 2013– | nationalteam2 = [[Indonesia national football team|Indonesia]] | nationalcaps2 = 19 | nationalgoals2 = 3 | nationalyears3 = 2018 | nationalteam3 = [[Indonesia national under-23 football team|Indonesia Olympic]] | nationalcaps3 = 5 | nationalgoals3 = 4 | medaltemplates = {{medalTeam|Indonesia}} {{MedalCompetition|[[AFF Championship]]}} {{medalRU|[[2016 AFF Championship|2016]]|Team}} | club-update = 18 September 2018 | nationalteam-update = 23:36, 2 December 2018 (UTC) }}
'''Stefano Yantje Lilipaly'''<ref>{{cite web|title=2016 AFF Suzuki Cup semifinal first leg match report|url=http://www.aseanfootball.org/results/2016AFFSuzukiCup-Match013.pdf|accessdate=6 December 2016|language=English}}</ref> (born 10 January 1990) is a Dutch-born [[Indonesians|Indonesian]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Stefano Lilipaly Tak Kapok Gabung Timnas Indonesia|url=http://www.republika.co.id/berita/sepakbola/liga-indonesia/13/06/11/mo7te0-stefano-lilipaly-tak-kapok-gabung-timnas-indonesia|accessdate=28 October 2014|language=Indonesian}}</ref> professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Midfielder|attacking midfielder]] or [[Winger (association football)|winger]] for [[Bali United F.C.|Bali United]] and the [[Indonesia national football team|Indonesia national team]].<ref name="Soccerway">{{cite web|title=Stefano Lilipaly|url=https://int.soccerway.com/players/stefano-lilipaly/136114/|work=Soccerway|publisher=Global Sports Media|accessdate=29 September 2011}}</ref> Born in the [[Netherlands]], Lilipaly represented his country of birth at youth level. Lilipaly made his debut for the [[Indonesia national football team|Indonesia national team]] in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=Stefano Lilipaly Puas dengan Debut di Timnas|url=http://www.tempo.co/read/news/2013/08/15/099504606/Stefano-Lilipaly-Puas-dengan-Debut-di-Timnas|accessdate=28 October 2014|language=Indonesian}}</ref> His father is [[Indonesians|Indonesian]] of [[Moluccans|Moluccan]] descent, while his mother is [[Dutch people|Dutch]].
== Club career == Lilipaly played for Dutch amateur side [[RKSV DCG]] for three years before joining [[Eredivisie]] club [[AZ (football club)|AZ]]'s academy in 2000.<ref name="Goal profile">{{cite web|title=Stefano Lilipaly, 'The Indonesian Iniesta'|url=http://www.goal.com/id-ID/news/1387/nasional/2011/01/05/2290451/profil-stefano-lilipaly-the-indonesian-iniesta|publisher=Goal|accessdate=29 September 2011|date=5 January 2011|language=Indonesian}}</ref> He moved to [[FC Utrecht|Utrecht]] the following year and progressed through their youth system.<ref name="Goal profile"/> Lilipaly made his first team debut for Utrecht in a [[2011–12 Eredivisie|league game]] at [[VVV-Venlo]] in August 2011,<ref>{{cite web|title=VVV vs. Utrecht 0–0|url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2011/08/06/netherlands/eredivisie/vvv-venlo/stichting-fc-utrecht/1120313/|work=Soccerway|publisher=Global Sports Media|accessdate=29 September 2011}}</ref> and his first appearance in the starting eleven came in January 2012, where he scored the opening goal against [[PSV Eindhoven|PSV]].<ref>{{cite web|title=PSV held to a draw by Utrecht|url=http://www.foxnews.com/sports/2012/01/22/psv-held-to-draw-by-utrecht/|publisher=Fox News|accessdate=23 January 2012|date=22 January 2012}}</ref> He played five times for Utrecht before joining [[Eerste Divisie]] club [[Almere City FC|Almere City]] on a free transfer in the summer of 2012.<ref name="Soccerway"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Paul Beekmans, Ricardo Kip en Stefano Lilipaly signeren contract bij Almere City FC|url=http://www.almerecity.nl/ac-1/paul-beekmans-ricardo-kip-en-stefano-lilipaly-signeren-contract-bij-almere-city-fc|publisher=Almere City FC|accessdate=16 August 2013|language=Dutch}}</ref>
===2017=== In January 2017 he joined [[Cambuur]] and he made his debut as late substitute against [[FC Utrecht]]. He made his first goal against [[Helmond Sport]], 3 February 2017. At this match Lilipaly made 2 assists at 3-0 won against Helmond Sports
== International career == Lilipaly represented the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]] at youth level, from the under-15s to under-18s.<ref name="Goal profile"/> He was eligible to represent the Netherlands or [[Indonesia national football team|Indonesia]] at full international level through his parents; his mother being Dutch and his father Indonesian.<ref name="Goal profile"/> Lilipaly took the Indonesian citizenship oath in October 2011,<ref>{{cite news|title=TelkomVision Tayangkan Penampilan Stefano Lilipaly|url=http://www.tribunnews.com/2011/09/18/telkomvision-tayangkan-penampilan-stefano-lilipaly|accessdate=10 October 2011|newspaper=Tribun News|date=18 September 2011|language=Indonesian}}</ref> to make him officially available for selection.<ref>{{cite web|title=Indonesia ready to import six stars|url=http://www.espnstar.com/football/asian-football/news/detail/item674909/Indonesia-ready-to-import-six-stars/|publisher=ESPN Star Sports|accessdate=10 October 2011|date=17 September 2011|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130102111906/http://www.espnstar.com/football/asian-football/news/detail/item674909/Indonesia-ready-to-import-six-stars/|archivedate=2 January 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Greg: Saya Akan Beri Yang Terbaik Bagi Timnas Indonesia|url=http://www.tribunnews.com/2011/10/10/greg-saya-akan-beri-yang-terbaik-bagi-timnas-indonesia|accessdate=10 October 2011|newspaper=Tribun News|date=10 October 2011|language=Indonesian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Lilipaly wordt Indonesisch international|url=http://www.rtvutrecht.nl/sport/393498|publisher=RTV Utrecht|accessdate=10 October 2011|language=Dutch|date=8 October 2011}}</ref> He made his full international debut in August 2013 in a win 2-0 against the [[Philippines national football team|Philippines]], when he made an assist for [[Greg Nwokolo]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Moore|first=Roy|title=Azkals still can't solve Indonesia problem, fall 2–0|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/322032/sports/football/azkals-still-can-t-solve-indonesia-problem-fall-2-0|publisher=GMA News|accessdate=16 August 2013|date=14 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Almo|first=Alder|title=Youthful Azkals bow to Indons, 2–0, in friendly|url=http://www.philstar.com/sports/2013/08/15/1094011/youthful-azkals-bow-indons-2-0-friendly|accessdate=16 August 2013|newspaper=The Philippine Star|date=15 August 2013}}</ref>
Lilipaly scored his first international goal for Indonesia in a match against Singapore in the [[2016 AFF Championship]], a late and decisive goal and made Indonesia qualified to the semifinal alongside [[Thailand national football team|Thailand]]. Lilipaly also score against Vietnam in the second leg semi-finals which sent Indonesia to the finals.
