{{Infobox person | name = William Bernard Ziff Sr. | image = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{birth date|1898|08|01}} | birth_place = | death_date = {{death date and age|1953|12|20|1898|08|01}} | death_place = | other_names = | education = | known_for = co-founder of [[Ziff Davis|Ziff Davis Inc.]] | occupation = businessman | nationality = United States | spouse = | parents = | children = [[William Bernard Ziff Jr.]] }}
'''William Bernard Ziff Sr.''' (August 1, 1898 &ndash; December 20, 1953) was an American publishing executive and author.
==Biography== He was born on August 1, 1898. He died on December 20, 1953.<ref>{{cite news |author= |coauthors= |title=W. B. Ziff; 55, Publisher And Author, Dies |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/chicagotribune/access/504550572.html?dids=504550572:504550572&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Dec+21,+1953&author=&pub=Chicago+Tribune&desc=W.+B.+ZIFF;+55,+PUBLISHER+AND+AUTHOR,+DIES&pqatl=google |quote=William Bernard Ziff, 55, a Chicagoan who built a magazine publishing empire and wrote several books, died yesterday in his hotel residence in... |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |date=December 21, 1953 |accessdate=2010-10-16 }}</ref> Ziff and [[Bernard G. Davis]] founded the magazine publisher [[Ziff Davis|Ziff Davis Inc.]] during 1927. After his death during 1953, his son [[William Bernard Ziff Jr.]] succeeded him at Ziff Davis.<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=William B. Ziff Jr., 76, Builder of Magazine Empire Dies |quote=William B. Ziff Jr., a publishing executive who made publications like Car and Driver and PC Magazine must reading among hobbyists and computer enthusiasts, died Saturday at his home in Pawling, N.Y. He was 76. |publisher=[[New York Times]] |date=September 12, 2006 }}</ref>
==Political views== Being of Jewish ancestry and motivated by the power of [[Nazi Germany]] during the 1930s, Ziff became one of the most prominent American endorsers of [[Revisionist Zionism]]. During 1935, he was persuaded by devotees of the Revisionist Zionist spokesman [[Ze'ev Jabotinsky]] to accept the presidency of the Zionist-Revisionists of America organization although he resigned after one year, being uncomfortable with his role as a Jewish organizational official. Ziff remained active with Zionist politics and caused controversy whan he authored during 1938 a criticism of British policy in the Holy Land entitled ''The Rape of Palestine.'' The [[British Foreign Office]] declared the book "violent and offensive" and monitored Ziff thereafter.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=vMl0-azdbVYC&pg=PT50&lpg=PT50&dq=American+Friends+of+a+Jewish+Palestine++ziff&source=bl&ots=GqDEcO1avu&sig=XYERd2o7D9BGlHyldq_5N3tqfM4&hl=en&sa=X&ei=8rh4T9v8I6bZ0QGSlo2yDQ&ved=0CCkQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=American%20Friends%20of%20a%20Jewish%20Palestine%20%20ziff&f=false "Militant Zionism in America: The Rise and Impact of the Jabotinsky Movement in the United States, 1926-1948" by Rafael Medoff] University Alabama Press; 1 edition (July 2, 2002) pp 39-40</ref><ref>[http://www.wymaninstitute.org/press/2004-02-18.php The David S. Wyman Institute for Holocaust Studies: "Unsung Hero of Holocaust Refugee Struggle Dies at 96"] February 18, 2004</ref>
